Sun Hung Kai Financial in Erroneous Buy Order for China Life

-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a   a n d   M a r c o   L u i
-- 
2011-09-09T09:58:20Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-09/sun-hung-kai-financial-in-erroneous-buy-order-for-china-life-2-.html
Sun Hung Kai Financial said it was
behind an erroneous buy order for shares of  China  Life Insurance
Co. in  Hong Kong  yesterday, and has “identified and rectified”
the problem.  The Sun Hung Kai & Co. unit “experienced an isolated
system glitch” at about 3:25 p.m. local time on Sept. 8,
resulting in the error, according to an e-mailed statement late
yesterday. “All trades for the day have been honored and no
clients were affected by this incident,” it said.  The firm didn’t say how many shares were involved in the
mistaken order. Hong Kong Exchanges & Clearing Ltd. said on its
 website  today that 82 million shares of China Life were traded
due to errors yesterday at HK$18.82 apiece, without naming the
companies involved in the trade.  A brokerage bid for 1.146 billion shares of China’s biggest
insurer at HK$18.82 each at 3:37 p.m. local time, according to
data compiled by Bloomberg. Almost 84 million shares changed
hands at that price yesterday, Bloomberg data show.  China Life, which had 7.4 billion shares available for
trading as of June 30, ended the day 0.2 percent higher at
HK$18.62 after climbing as high as HK$18.94.  Shares of Sun Hung Kai Co. rose 3.3 percent to close at
HK$5.27 today, compared with the 0.2 percent decline in the
benchmark  Hang Seng Index. (HSI)  China Life, which tumbled 41 percent
this year through yesterday, rose 2.8 percent to HK$19.14.  To contact the reporters on this story:
